subsection.p:
      Vector equationequivalence with system of equations
      An equation involving vectors with n coordinates is the same as n equations involving only numbers.  For example, the equation
    x\vec{1 2 6} + y \vec{-1 -2 -1} = \vec{8 16 3}
    simplifies to
    \vec{ x 2x 6x} + \vec{-y -2y -y} = \vec{8 16 3}
\sptxt{or}
\spalignsysdelims()\syseq{ x - y; 2x - 2y; 6x - y} = \vec{8 16 3}.

    For two vectors to be equal, all of their coordinates must be equal, so this is just the system of linear equations
    \spalignsysdelims\{.\syseq{x - y = 8; 2x - 2y = 16; 6x - y = 3\rlap.}

In order to actually solve the vector equation
    x\textcolor{seq-red}{\vec{1 2 6}}
    + y \textcolor{seq-green}{\vec{-1 -2 -1}}
    = \textcolor{seq-blue}{\vec{8 16 3}},
    one has to solve the system of linear equations
    \spalignsysdelims\{.\syseq{x - y = 8; 2x - 2y = 16; 6x - y = 3\rlap.}
    This means forming the augmented matrix
    \def\r{\color{seq-red}}\def\g{\color{seq-green}}\def\b{\color{seq-blue}}
    \amat{\r1 \g-1 \b8; \r2 \g-2 \b16; \r6 \g-1 \b3}
    and row reducing.  Note that the columns of the augmented matrix are the vectors from the original vector equation, so it is not actually necessary to write the system of equations: one can go directly from the vector equation to the augmented matrix by smooshing the vectors together.  In the following  we carry out the row reduction and find the solution.

Now we have three equivalent ways of thinking about a linear system:


As a system of equations:
        \syseq{2x_1 + 3x_2 - 2x_3 = 7; x_1 - x_2 - 3x_3 = 5}



As an augmented matrix:
        \amat{2 3 -2 7; 1 -1 -3 5}


As a vector equation (x_1v_1 + x_2v_2 + \cdots + x_nv_n = b):
        x_1\vec{2 1} + x_2\vec{3 -1} + x_3\vec{-2 -3} = \vec{7 5}


    The third is geometric in nature: it lends itself to drawing pictures.

image.latex-image-code:

\begin{tikzpicture}[thin border nodes, scale=.9]
\begin{scope}
  \draw[grid lines] (-3,-2) grid (4, 3);
  \path[clip] (-3,-2) rectangle (4, 3);
  \draw[thin, seq4] ($-2*(2,1)$) -- ($2*(2,1)$);
  \node[seq4,whitebg] at (0,2) {$\Span\{v\}$};
  \draw[vector, seq1] (0,0) to["$v$"] (2,1);
  \point at (0,0);
\end{scope}

\begin{scope}[xshift=8cm]
  \draw[grid lines] (-3,-2) grid (4, 3);
  \fill[seq4!30, nearly transparent] (-3,-2) rectangle (4,3);
  \node[seq4] at (.5,2.5) {$\Span\{v,w\}$};
  \draw[vector, seq1] (0,-1) to["$v$"] (1,1);
  \draw[vector, seq2] (0,-1) to["\strut$w$"'] (1,-1);
  \point at (0,-1);
\end{scope}

\begin{scope}[xshift=4cm, yshift=-7cm]
  \draw[grid lines] (-3,-3) grid (4, 4);
  \path[clip] (-3,-3) rectangle (4, 4);
  \node[seq4] at (.5,2.5) {$\Span\{v,w\}$};
  \draw[thin, seq4] ($-2*(2,2)$) -- ($2*(2,2)$);
  \draw[vector, seq1] (0,0) to["$v$"] (2,2);
  \draw[vector, seq2] (0,0) to["$w$"' pos=.4] (-1,-1);
  \point at (0,0);
\end{scope}
\end{tikzpicture}


